('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:exam:8e4a1607', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "N1", "question": "<p>Identify which of these networks is best described as a WAN rather than a LAN.</p>", "options": ["A network connecting a supermarket chain''s stores in different cities across the country", "A network connecting six computers in a single classroom to one shared printer", "A network connecting the till and stockroom computer in one small shop", "A home network connecting a laptop and a phone to a single Wi-Fi router"], "hint": "Look for the option that covers a large geographical area spanning more than one site."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>A network connecting a supermarket chain''s stores in different cities across the country</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>The other three options all describe a network confined to a single site, which is a LAN, not a WAN.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "A network connecting a supermarket chain''s stores in different cities across the country."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:exam:a85d5688', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "N2", "question": "<p>Keswick Design Studio wants a piece of hardware that will let its four PCs and one server share files and a printer within the same office. Identify the hardware that does this job.</p>", "options": ["A switch", "A router", "A DNS server", "A web server"], "caseStudy": "<p>Keswick Design Studio is a small graphic design company based in a single rented office. It has four desktop PCs and one dedicated file server, all connected together with cables so staff can share design files and a network printer.</p>", "hint": "Think about which device connects multiple wired devices together within one LAN, rather than connecting to a different network."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>A switch</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>A router connects different networks together, and a DNS server/web server play no role in wiring devices together within one office LAN.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "A switch."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:exam:663cc885', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "N3", "question": "<p>Identify what a DNS server converts a URL into.</p>", "options": ["The matching IP address", "A backup copy of the website''s files", "An encrypted version of the same URL", "The physical location of the web server''s building"], "caseStudy": "<p>A customer opens their web browser and types www.brightweb-shop.co.uk to visit an online shop''s website, which is stored on a web server owned by the shop''s hosting company.</p>", "hint": "DNS''s entire job is one specific conversion — think about what a computer actually needs in order to contact a web server."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>The matching IP address</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul>\n<li>DNS performs a lookup only; it does not store files, encrypt data, or record physical locations.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "The matching IP address."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:b5df85ab', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these best describes a Wide Area Network (WAN)?", "options": ["A network spanning a large area, such as multiple cities or countries", "A network that only ever connects exactly two computers directly together, without any hardware", "A network confined to a single building or a small group of nearby buildings", "A network that can only ever be built using wireless access points and never any cables"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A WAN covers a large geographical area, unlike the other options, which either describe a LAN or describe made-up restrictions that don''t define any real network type."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:bf1fdd22', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A company owns and fully manages every switch and cable inside its head office network. What does this tell you about that network?", "options": ["It is most likely a LAN, since the organisation itself owns its infrastructure", "It must be a WAN, since owning hardware always means covering a large area", "It cannot be considered a genuine network at all unless it has a router connecting it out to the wider Internet", "It proves the company has no wireless devices anywhere on its premises"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Full ownership and control of the infrastructure by a single organisation, confined to one site, is characteristic of a LAN — WANs typically rely on infrastructure leased from telecoms providers."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:fe77e882', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why does a network typically feel slower when many devices are actively transferring data at the same time?", "options": ["Because the available bandwidth is shared, so each device gets a smaller portion of it", "Because every device automatically and permanently halves its own processing speed once it first connects", "Because wireless connections switch off completely once ten devices are joined", "Because routers can only ever process data from a single connected device"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Bandwidth is the finite amount of data a connection can carry in a given time; more devices actively using it at once means less of it is available to each device."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:5f0e173a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which transmission medium generally offers the fastest speeds and is unaffected by electrical interference?", "options": ["Fibre-optic cable, which carries data as pulses of light through glass", "Standard copper cable, since it has been used in networks for the longest time", "Wireless radio signals, since no cabling is involved at all", "Any transmission medium performs identically once installed correctly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Fibre-optic cable sends data as light through glass strands, giving it very high speeds and immunity to the electrical interference that affects copper cable."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:ded0bc20', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "In a client-server network, what is the defining role of a client computer?", "options": ["It requests and makes use of services or resources provided by a server", "It permanently stores every other device''s files as an automatic backup", "It converts wireless signals into wired signals for the rest of the network", "It manages user accounts and security settings for the whole network"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Clients are the computers that request and use the services (files, printing, accounts) that a dedicated server provides — that request-and-use relationship is the defining feature."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:6b3cea3c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is a genuine disadvantage of a peer-to-peer network compared to a client-server network?", "options": ["It is generally harder to keep data secure and consistently backed up across all peers", "It always requires noticeably far more expensive specialist hardware than any client-server network ever needs", "It cannot physically connect more than two computers together at once", "It automatically stops working the moment more than one file is shared"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Without one dedicated, centrally managed server, security and backups depend on each individual peer, which is much harder to guarantee consistently than in a managed client-server setup."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:724b0979', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the purpose of a NIC (network interface card)?", "options": ["It is the hardware that lets a computer physically connect to a network", "It converts a URL into the matching IP address for a website", "It permanently stores every one of a website''s files so browsers can request and load them instantly", "It boosts a wireless signal so it reaches devices much further away"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A NIC is the piece of hardware, built in or fitted, that allows a device to physically join a network — every networked device, wired or wireless, needs one."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:f4a6abf9', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the key difference between what a switch does and what a router does?", "options": ["A switch connects devices within one LAN; a router connects one network to another network", "A switch only works wirelessly, while a router only works using copper cable", "A switch and a router actually perform exactly the same underlying job, just marketed and sold under two completely different product names", "A switch stores webpages, while a router looks up IP addresses using DNS"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A switch forwards data between devices that are already part of the same LAN, whereas a router directs data between separate networks, such as a LAN and the Internet."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:edf69396', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A wired office network wants to let staff connect their phones and laptops wirelessly. Which device makes this possible?", "options": ["A wireless access point (WAP)", "An additional length of fibre-optic transmission cable", "A second router configured to ignore all wireless requests", "A switch with its wireless functionality permanently disabled"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A WAP converts between the wired network''s signals and wireless radio signals, letting wireless devices join a network that was originally built using cables."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:a775ab01', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the main purpose of a DNS server on the Internet?", "options": ["To look up the IP address that matches a URL a user has typed in", "To permanently store the actual files of every website in the world", "To physically deliver data packets between two nearby wireless devices", "To decide which websites a school''s students are and aren''t allowed to visit"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "DNS''s job is the lookup itself — converting the human-readable URL into the numerical IP address a browser needs in order to actually contact the correct web server."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:ff91df63', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "How does a URL differ from an IP address?", "options": ["A URL is the human-readable address typed in; an IP address is the numerical address devices use", "A URL is always longer in length than any IP address could ever be", "An IP address is only ever used for accessing websites, while a URL can be used for absolutely any device on any network", "A URL and an IP address are simply two different names for the exact same thing"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A URL (like www.example.com) is written for people to read and type; the matching IP address is the numerical form that computers actually use to route data."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:mcq:b14c7a8f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why is a star topology generally considered less resilient than a mesh topology?", "options": ["A single failure of its central switch can bring down the entire network", "It requires far more total cabling than a mesh topology of the same size", "It cannot ever be used to connect more than two devices at once", "Every device in a star topology must share one single physical cable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Because every device in a star topology depends on the one central switch, that single device failing takes the whole network down — a risk a mesh topology avoids by having no central point."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:a64c881d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A LAN is normally confined to a single site, such as one building."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a LAN''s defining feature is its small geographical scale, usually one site or a small group of nearby buildings."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:fc778865', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Bandwidth is unlimited, so having more users on a network never affects its performance."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Bandwidth is finite and shared between everyone using the connection at once — more active users means a smaller share, and slower performance, for each."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:f03c0a63', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "In a client-server network, every computer has exactly equal status, with no dedicated server."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "That describes a peer-to-peer network. In a client-server network, one or more dedicated servers provide services that client computers request and use."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:b923e979', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A switch connects devices together within a single LAN."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a switch forwards data between wired devices that are already part of the same LAN."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:380842a9', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A router''s main job is to connect one network to a different network."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a router directs data between separate networks, most commonly a LAN and the Internet, unlike a switch which works within one LAN."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:ed587e0e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "DNS stores the actual files of every website so browsers can display them instantly."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "DNS only looks up the IP address matching a URL — it does not store website content. The website''s files are stored on a web server."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:f0a65624', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Storing data in the cloud means it is not stored on any physical hardware anywhere."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Cloud storage still uses real physical servers — just ones owned and managed by someone else (a cloud provider), accessed over the Internet rather than stored locally."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tf:690b28c6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A mesh topology generally needs more cabling than a star topology connecting the same number of devices."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — a mesh topology''s n(n − 1) ÷ 2 cabling rule grows much faster than a star topology''s one-cable-per-device requirement."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:9c3cb2ea', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What''s the difference between a LAN and a WAN?", "reading": "<h4>Two networks, defined by scale</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>LAN (Local Area Network)</strong> connects devices across a small geographical area — usually a single site, such as one building or a small group of nearby buildings (a school, an office, a home).</li>\n<li>A <strong>WAN (Wide Area Network)</strong> connects devices across a large geographical area — different cities, different countries, or the whole globe.</li>\n<li>The <strong>Internet</strong> is itself the largest WAN in existence: a worldwide collection of interconnected networks, not owned by any single organisation.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Who owns and controls the infrastructure?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A LAN''s cabling, switches and other hardware are normally owned and fully controlled by the single organisation that uses it — a school''s IT department owns and manages its own LAN.</li>\n<li>A WAN usually relies on infrastructure that is NOT entirely owned by the organisation using it. Connecting distant sites means renting/leasing lines and equipment from telecommunications companies, who own and maintain the wider infrastructure in between.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Everyday examples</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>LAN examples:</strong> the computers in one school building; a small office''s network; a home Wi-Fi network.</li>\n<li><strong>WAN examples:</strong> a bank''s network connecting branches in different cities; a supermarket chain linking its stores nationwide; the Internet itself.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which of these is the clearest example of a WAN rather than a LAN?", "options": ["A network spanning many cities, connecting a company''s branches nationwide", "A network inside a single small classroom connecting six laptops to one shared printer", "A network connecting the computers in one office to a shared local server", "A home network connecting a laptop and a phone to one Wi-Fi router"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A WAN covers a large geographical area — multiple cities in this case — whereas the other three options describe devices confined to a single site, which is a LAN."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:a204b401', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What factors affect how well a network performs?", "reading": "<h4>Bandwidth — and sharing it</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Bandwidth</strong> is the maximum amount of data that can be transferred across a network connection in a given time.</li>\n<li>Bandwidth is <strong>shared</strong> between everyone using the connection at once. The more users or devices actively sending/receiving data at the same time, the smaller each one''s share becomes — which is why a school network can feel much slower at busy times of day.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Number of users and devices</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Simply having more devices <strong>connected</strong> to a network does not by itself slow it down — but more devices <strong>actively transferring data at the same time</strong> means more competition for the same limited bandwidth, and therefore slower performance for everyone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Transmission media</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Copper cable</strong> is cheap and widely used, but slower than fibre and more affected by electrical interference.</li>\n<li><strong>Fibre-optic cable</strong> sends data as pulses of light through glass strands — much faster than copper and unaffected by electrical interference, but more expensive to install.</li>\n<li><strong>Wireless</strong> connections are convenient (no cables needed) but are generally slower and less reliable than a wired connection of the same quality.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Interference, latency and distance from a wireless access point</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Interference</strong> — from other wireless devices, thick walls, or electrical equipment — can weaken or corrupt a signal, forcing data to be resent and slowing the network down.</li>\n<li><strong>Latency</strong> is the delay between data being sent and it arriving at its destination; a longer physical distance, or data passing through more devices along the way, increases latency.</li>\n<li>The <strong>further a wireless device is from its access point</strong>, the weaker its signal, which usually means a slower and less reliable connection.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why can a school''s wireless network feel noticeably slower at busy times of the school day?", "options": ["More devices are actively sharing the same limited bandwidth at once", "Wireless signals always slow down permanently once a school day begins", "The school''s router automatically reduces its own performance overnight", "Bandwidth only ever affects wired connections, never wireless ones"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Bandwidth is shared. When many devices are actively transferring data at the same time, each one gets a smaller share of the available bandwidth, so the network feels slower."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:eeec5065', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Client-server vs peer-to-peer networks", "reading": "<h4>The roles of the computers involved</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>In a <strong>client-server</strong> network, one or more dedicated, powerful central computers (<strong>servers</strong>) provide services and resources — such as storing files, managing user accounts, or controlling a shared printer. Other computers (<strong>clients</strong>) request and use those services.</li>\n<li>In a <strong>peer-to-peer (P2P)</strong> network, every computer (a <strong>peer</strong>, or node) has equal status. Each one can act as both a client and a server, sharing files or resources directly with other peers — there is no single dedicated managing machine.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Client-server: advantages and disadvantages</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Advantage:</strong> centralised control makes it far easier to manage security, user accounts and backups from one place.</li>\n<li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> it needs a dedicated, often expensive server plus IT expertise to maintain it — and if the server fails, the whole network''s shared services can be disrupted.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Peer-to-peer: advantages and disadvantages</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Advantage:</strong> cheap and simple to set up, since no dedicated server or extra hardware is required.</li>\n<li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> harder to keep secure and consistently backed up, since data is spread across many individual peers rather than managed centrally — this makes it unsuitable for large organisations.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Typical use cases</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Client-server</strong> suits schools, businesses and any setting where centralised control, security and reliability matter.</li>\n<li><strong>Peer-to-peer</strong> suits small, informal networks — a handful of home computers sharing files directly, or a small club with no budget for a dedicated server.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In a client-server network, what is the role of the server?", "options": ["It provides shared services and resources that client computers request and use", "It is simply the first computer that was ever connected to the network", "It only stores a backup copy of data in case a client computer breaks", "It physically converts wireless radio signals into wired network signals for every other connected device"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The server is the dedicated computer that provides services (files, accounts, printing) which client computers then request and use — that is its defining role."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:ba05348e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What hardware connects stand-alone computers into a LAN?", "reading": "<h4>NIC — Network Interface Card</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>NIC</strong> is the hardware, built into or fitted inside a computer, that lets it physically connect to a network. Every networked device needs one, wired or wireless.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Switch vs router — the key distinction</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>switch</strong> connects multiple wired devices together <strong>within the same LAN</strong>. It reads the destination address of each piece of data and forwards it only to the specific device it is meant for, rather than sending it to every device.</li>\n<li>A <strong>router</strong> connects <strong>different networks</strong> together — most commonly, it connects a LAN to another network such as the Internet, directing (routing) data between the two based on IP addresses.</li>\n<li><strong>The distinction that matters for the exam:</strong> a switch works within one LAN, joining devices to each other; a router works between networks, joining one network to another.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>WAP — Wireless Access Point</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>WAP</strong> allows wireless devices to join a wired LAN. It converts between the wired network''s signals and wireless radio signals, so a laptop or phone can connect without a cable.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Transmission media</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The physical (or wireless) pathway the data actually travels along — <strong>copper cable</strong>, <strong>fibre-optic cable</strong>, or <strong>wireless</strong> radio signals — is what physically links all of this hardware together into one working LAN.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A small office already has a working wired LAN. Which piece of hardware would let staff also connect their laptops wirelessly to that same LAN?", "options": ["A wireless access point (WAP)", "A second network interface card fitted inside the existing switch", "A router configured to only forward data to wired devices", "A longer length of fibre-optic transmission cable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A wireless access point converts between the wired LAN''s signals and wireless radio signals, letting wireless devices join a network that was originally built using cables."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:bbcc902d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The Internet, DNS and hosting", "reading": "<h4>Web servers, clients, URLs and IP addresses</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>web server</strong> stores a website''s files and sends them to a device when requested. The <strong>client</strong> is the user''s device (running a browser) making that request.</li>\n<li>A <strong>URL</strong> (e.g. www.example.com) is the human-readable web address a person types in. An <strong>IP address</strong> (e.g. 192.168.1.1) is the numerical address that computers actually use to find and communicate with each other across a network.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>DNS — how a lookup actually works</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>Domain Name System (DNS)</strong> is a distributed system of servers whose job is to convert a URL into the matching IP address, step by step:</li>\n<li><strong>Step 1:</strong> the browser first checks whether it already has that URL''s IP address stored (cached) from a previous visit.</li>\n<li><strong>Step 2:</strong> if not, the browser sends the URL to a DNS server.</li>\n<li><strong>Step 3:</strong> the DNS server looks up the matching IP address in its own records — or, if it does not hold that record, asks another DNS server on the DNS server''s behalf.</li>\n<li><strong>Step 4:</strong> the DNS server returns the correct IP address to the browser, which then uses it to request the actual webpage from the correct web server.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Hosting</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hosting</strong> means storing a website''s files on a web server — usually rented space paid for by the website''s owner — so the site is accessible over the Internet at any time.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The Cloud: benefits and drawbacks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The cloud</strong> means storing data, or running software, on remote servers accessed over the Internet, rather than on local hardware you own.</li>\n<li><strong>Benefits:</strong> data can be accessed from anywhere with an Internet connection; backups and maintenance are handled by the provider; storage can be scaled up easily without buying new hardware; several people can collaborate on the same files.</li>\n<li><strong>Drawbacks:</strong> a reliable Internet connection is required to access your own data; there is usually an ongoing subscription cost; you are trusting a third party with your data''s security and privacy; you have no control if an outage happens at the provider''s end.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What job does a DNS server actually do?", "options": ["It converts a URL that a user types in into the matching IP address", "It permanently stores every website''s files so they load faster for everyone", "It physically connects a school''s wired LAN to its wireless devices", "It encrypts a user''s password before it is sent to a website"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "DNS looks up the numerical IP address that matches the human-readable URL a user has typed, so the browser knows which web server to actually contact."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:d91f15ba', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Star topology", "reading": "<h4>How a star topology is wired</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Every device connects <strong>individually</strong> to one central device (usually a switch), each with its own dedicated cable. There are no direct connections between the other devices themselves.</li>\n<li>Data sent from one device to another always passes through the central device first, which then forwards it on to the correct destination.</li>\n</ul>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 240 220\" width=\"220\" height=\"202\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Star topology diagram: a central switch connected by its own individual cable to four separate PCs and a server, arranged around it — no device is connected directly to another device\">\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"24\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"211\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"176\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"64\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"29\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<rect x=\"104\" y=\"104\" width=\"32\" height=\"32\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"124\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">SW</text>\n<circle cx=\"120\" cy=\"24\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"28\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC1</text>\n<circle cx=\"211\" cy=\"90\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"211\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC2</text>\n<circle cx=\"176\" cy=\"198\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"176\" y=\"202\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC3</text>\n<circle cx=\"64\" cy=\"198\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"64\" y=\"202\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC4</text>\n<circle cx=\"29\" cy=\"90\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"29\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">SRV</text>\n</svg>\n<h4>Advantages of a star topology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If one cable or one non-central device fails, only that single device is affected — the rest of the network keeps working normally.</li>\n<li>Performance stays consistent and fast, since each device has its own dedicated cable rather than sharing one single line with everyone else.</li>\n<li>New devices are easy to add — just run a new cable to the central device.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Disadvantages of a star topology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If the central device (the switch) fails, the <strong>whole network</strong> goes down, since every device relies on it.</li>\n<li>It needs more cabling overall than some alternative layouts, since every single device needs its own separate cable back to the centre.</li>\n<li>Adding a device requires a free port on the central switch — once the switch''s ports are full, it must be replaced or another switch added.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In a star topology, what happens if the central switch fails completely?", "options": ["The whole network stops working, because every device depends on the switch", "Nothing at all changes, because every device is also already connected directly to each other", "Only the single closest device to the switch loses its connection", "The network automatically rewires itself into a mesh topology"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Every device''s own cable in a star topology leads only to the central switch, so if that one central device fails, the entire network loses its connections."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:learn:c7e514ab', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Mesh topology", "reading": "<h4>How a mesh topology is wired</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>In a (full) mesh topology, <strong>every device connects directly to every other device</strong> — there is no central device that the others depend on.</li>\n<li>The number of cables needed grows quickly as devices are added, following the rule <strong>n(n − 1) ÷ 2</strong> for n devices — 5 devices need 5 × 4 ÷ 2 = <strong>10</strong> separate cables.</li>\n</ul>\n<svg viewBox=\"0 0 240 220\" width=\"220\" height=\"202\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Mesh topology diagram: four PCs and a server, with every device connected directly to every other device by its own cable — ten cables in total, no central device\">\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"24\" x2=\"211\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"24\" x2=\"176\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"24\" x2=\"64\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"120\" y1=\"24\" x2=\"29\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"211\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"176\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"211\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"64\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"211\" y1=\"90\" x2=\"29\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"176\" y1=\"198\" x2=\"64\" y2=\"198\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"176\" y1=\"198\" x2=\"29\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<line x1=\"64\" y1=\"198\" x2=\"29\" y2=\"90\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<circle cx=\"120\" cy=\"24\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"120\" y=\"28\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC1</text>\n<circle cx=\"211\" cy=\"90\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"211\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC2</text>\n<circle cx=\"176\" cy=\"198\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"176\" y=\"202\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC3</text>\n<circle cx=\"64\" cy=\"198\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"64\" y=\"202\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">PC4</text>\n<circle cx=\"29\" cy=\"90\" r=\"15\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text x=\"29\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"currentColor\">SRV</text>\n</svg>\n<h4>Advantages of a mesh topology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Highly <strong>resilient</strong> — if one cable or device fails, data can simply be re-routed along a different path, so the rest of the network keeps working.</li>\n<li>There is no single central device whose failure could bring down the whole network, unlike a star topology''s switch.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Disadvantages of a mesh topology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Needs <strong>far more cabling</strong> as devices are added — the n(n − 1) ÷ 2 rule means the number of cables grows much faster than the number of devices.</li>\n<li>More expensive and much more complex to install, wire and maintain than a star topology, especially as the network grows.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Choosing between them</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>star</strong> topology suits most everyday offices and schools, where keeping cost and complexity down matters, and an occasional (rare) switch failure is an acceptable risk.</li>\n<li>A <strong>mesh</strong> topology suits systems that must almost never go down regardless of cost — for example, emergency-services communications or a data centre — because it has no single point of failure.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why is a mesh topology generally considered more resilient than a star topology?", "options": ["It has no single central device whose failure could bring down the whole network", "It always uses fewer cables in total than a star topology needs", "It only ever needs one shared cable connecting every device together", "It automatically detects and repairs any damaged cable itself, without any human intervention required"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Because every device connects directly to every other device, there is no central point (like a star''s switch) that the whole network depends on — one failure can be routed around."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:04d113b2', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing a switch and a router do exactly the same job, just under two different names.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A <strong>switch</strong> connects devices <em>within</em> the same LAN, forwarding data only to the device it''s addressed to. A <strong>router</strong> connects <em>different networks</em> together — most commonly, a LAN to the Internet. One works inside a network; the other works between networks.</p>", "question": "Which statement correctly separates what a switch does from what a router does?", "options": ["A switch works within one LAN; a router connects that LAN to a different network", "A switch and a router perform identical jobs, just marketed under different names", "A router only ever works wirelessly, while a switch only works using cables", "A switch stores webpages, while a router looks up matching IP addresses"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A switch''s job is entirely within one LAN (device-to-device); a router''s job is connecting that LAN to a separate network, such as the Internet."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:14af0a42', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming a wireless connection is always faster than a wired one, since Wi-Fi feels newer and more convenient.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A good wired connection — especially fibre-optic cable — is generally <strong>faster and more reliable</strong> than wireless. Wireless is convenient because it removes cables, but it is more affected by interference and distance from the access point, and typically slower than an equivalent wired link.</p>", "question": "Why is a wired fibre-optic connection generally considered faster and more reliable than a wireless one?", "options": ["It is less affected by interference and does not weaken with distance from an access point the way wireless does", "Wireless connections are physically and completely incapable of ever transferring more than a few tiny bytes of data at once", "All wired connections are automatically free, while every wireless connection has a cost", "Fibre-optic cable is a form of wireless technology that simply looks like a cable"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Wireless signals weaken with distance and can be disrupted by interference; a wired connection, especially fibre, avoids both issues, which is why it''s typically faster and more consistent."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:91eb4c7a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a mesh topology, like a star, still relies on one central device that every connection passes through.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A mesh topology has <strong>no central device</strong> at all — every device connects <em>directly</em> to every other device. It is a star topology that relies on one central device (usually a switch), which is exactly why a mesh is more resilient to a single point of failure.</p>", "question": "Does a mesh topology rely on one central device that every other device connects through?", "options": ["No — every device connects directly to every other device, with no central device", "Yes — a mesh topology always uses a central switch device, exactly just like a star topology does", "Yes, but only when there are fewer than three devices connected", "No — a mesh topology uses no cables of any kind between its devices"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The defining feature of a mesh topology is direct device-to-device connections with no central point — that''s what makes it resilient to any single device failing."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:716f197a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Assuming more bandwidth always guarantees a faster network, no matter how many devices are using it at once.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Bandwidth only sets the <strong>maximum</strong> a connection can carry. Real performance still depends on how many users or devices are <em>actively</em> competing for that same bandwidth at any one moment — a high-bandwidth connection shared by hundreds of active users can still feel slow.</p>", "question": "A network has very high bandwidth, but 200 devices are streaming video on it at the same time. What is most likely to happen?", "options": ["Performance can still slow down, because the bandwidth is shared between all the active devices", "Performance is completely guaranteed to stay fast at all times, regardless of how many devices are actively connected", "The extra devices will have no effect at all on the network''s available bandwidth", "Bandwidth automatically increases itself whenever more devices connect"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Bandwidth is a shared, finite resource. Even a high-bandwidth connection can slow down once enough devices are actively competing for a share of it at the same time."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:f3db4449', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Believing the cloud is some kind of storage that exists without any physical hardware, literally ''in the sky''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Cloud storage is still stored on <strong>real, physical servers</strong> — just servers owned and managed by someone else, in a data centre, accessed remotely over the Internet rather than on hardware you own locally.</p>", "question": "Is data stored ''in the cloud'' stored without using any physical storage hardware at all?", "options": ["No — it is stored on real physical servers owned by a cloud provider, accessed over the Internet", "Yes — cloud data exists purely as radio signals with no physical storage involved", "Yes, because cloud storage providers never use any physical data centres or storage equipment whatsoever", "No — but only for the first year of a paid cloud storage subscription"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Cloud storage is real, physical storage — just located on a provider''s own servers rather than the user''s local device — accessed remotely over an Internet connection."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:misc:c14574a3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Describing the LAN/WAN difference only by ''a WAN is just a really big LAN'', without mentioning ownership of the infrastructure.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Scale is only half the answer. A LAN''s infrastructure is normally owned and controlled by the single organisation using it, while a WAN typically relies on infrastructure <strong>leased from telecommunications companies</strong> that connect distant sites together — a full answer should mention both scale AND who controls the infrastructure.</p>", "question": "Besides geographical scale, what else usually distinguishes a WAN from a LAN?", "options": ["Who owns and controls the network infrastructure being used", "The total number of computers connected, regardless of location", "Whether the network uses electricity to transfer any of its data", "Whether the network was installed before or after the year 2000"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A full comparison includes ownership: a LAN''s infrastructure is usually owned by the one organisation using it, while a WAN typically relies on infrastructure leased from telecoms providers."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tips:2bea9326', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Command-word ladder: a 4-mark ''describe'' on the DNS lookup process", "reading": "<p>A typical question: <em>\"Describe how a DNS lookup converts a URL into the correct IP address.\"</em> [4 marks] The same idea, shown at every level:</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ 0-1 marks:</strong> \"DNS finds the website''s address.\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>True in spirit, but far too vague to be creditable — it doesn''t describe a PROCESS at all, just restates what DNS is for.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>⚠️ 2 marks:</strong> \"The browser sends the URL to a DNS server, which looks up the matching IP address and sends it back.\"</p>\n<ul>\n<li>This captures the middle of the process, but skips the browser''s own cache check at the start and what happens once the IP address comes back.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>✅ 4 marks:</strong> \"First the browser checks its own cache for the IP address. If it isn''t there, the browser sends the URL to a DNS server. The DNS server looks up the matching IP address in its records (asking another DNS server if needed). Finally, the DNS server returns the IP address to the browser, which uses it to request the page from the correct web server.\"</p>\n\n<p><strong>Why this matters:</strong> \"describe how X works\" questions on this topic are almost always marked as a numbered SEQUENCE of steps, one mark per genuine step. Naming DNS''s purpose is not the same as describing its process — write the steps in order, and don''t skip the first one (checking the cache) or the last one (using the IP address that comes back).</p>", "question": "A student answers ''Describe how a DNS lookup works'' by writing only ''DNS looks up IP addresses for websites''. Why does this likely score very few of the 4 marks?", "options": ["It states the purpose of DNS but doesn''t describe the actual step-by-step process", "It is factually incorrect about what DNS does for a website", "It is far too long and detailed an answer for a 4-mark question to ever reward fully", "DNS lookups cannot be described in words, only diagrams can be credited"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "''Describe how'' questions need the actual sequence of steps — checking cache, contacting a DNS server, the lookup, returning the IP address — not just a restatement of DNS''s overall purpose."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tips:1058b2a6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — ''Give one advantage and one disadvantage'' — don''t double up on one side", "reading": "<p>This exact style of question appears constantly on this topic — comparing topologies, client-server vs peer-to-peer, cloud vs local storage, wired vs wireless. The trap is always the same.</p>\n\n<p><strong>❌ The trap:</strong> writing two advantages (or two disadvantages) because you''re more confident about one side, hoping both will count. They won''t — the mark scheme groups the marks as ONE for a genuine advantage and ONE for a genuine disadvantage, so two advantages score only half marks at best, never full marks.</p>\n\n<p><strong>✅ The reliable method:</strong> before writing anything, plan explicitly: \"Advantage: ___. Disadvantage: ___.\" One clear sentence for each, addressing BOTH sides the question actually asked for.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Worked example — cloud storage vs local storage:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Advantage:</strong> data stored in the cloud can be accessed from any device with an Internet connection, not just the one it was saved on.</li>\n<li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> accessing that data depends entirely on having a working Internet connection — no connection means no access, even to your own files.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A question asks for one advantage and one disadvantage of cloud storage [2 marks]. A student writes two separate advantages, no disadvantage. What is the maximum they can score?", "options": ["1 mark, since only one genuine advantage can be credited without any disadvantage given", "2 marks, since two separate correct points about cloud storage were made in total across the answer", "0 marks, because the question specifically required exactly one sentence", "2 marks, as long as both advantages are longer than three lines each"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The mark scheme awards one mark for a genuine advantage and one for a genuine disadvantage. With no disadvantage attempted, only the advantage mark is available — maximum 1 of 2."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies:tips:77e0f2d6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:1-3-1-networks-and-topologies', '1.3.1 Networks and Topologies', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — The 8-mark ''discuss'' ladder: choosing between star and mesh", "reading": "<p>An 8-mark discuss question gives you a scenario and asks you to weigh up a choice — here, star vs mesh topology for a given organisation. Roughly 10-12 minutes; plan before writing.</p>\n\n<p><strong>The structure that reaches the top band:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1. How each topology is wired</strong> — briefly state the mechanism of both (star = central device, mesh = every device to every other device) so the marker knows you understand what you''re comparing.</li>\n<li><strong>2. A chain for topology A</strong> — factor → effect → consequence. E.g. \"a star topology needs less cabling (factor) → which keeps installation cost and complexity down (effect) → making it affordable for an organisation with a limited IT budget (consequence).\"</li>\n<li><strong>3. A counterpoint</strong> — the same factor from the OTHER topology''s side. E.g. \"however, the star topology''s single point of failure at the switch means one fault can take down the entire network.\"</li>\n<li><strong>4. A second, different issue</strong> — don''t just repeat cabling; also weigh resilience, or cost, or scalability, depending which you haven''t covered yet.</li>\n<li><strong>5. A separate, justified conclusion</strong> — state which topology suits THIS scenario specifically, and why, rather than which topology is \"better\" in general.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Why this matters:</strong> the top mark band on OCR''s discuss questions rewards weighing BOTH sides against the actual scenario given, not simply listing everything you know about star and mesh topologies in general.</p>", "question": "An 8-mark ''discuss'' answer lists five correct facts about star and mesh topologies, but never applies any of them to the scenario given in the question. Which band is this most likely to land in?", "options": ["A lower band, since the top band requires the discussion to be applied to the given scenario", "The top band automatically, since every single fact that was listed happens to be technically accurate", "Zero marks, since listing facts is never creditable on any exam question", "It cannot be marked at all without a diagram included in the answer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Correct but generic facts, never applied to the specific scenario, are exactly what keeps a discuss answer out of the top band — application to context is what the higher bands reward."}'::jsonb),
